<p class="body">The word "Java" does a lot of work in coffee, and most of it creates confusion. Grocery store shelves use it as a synonym for coffee in general. Commodity buyers use it to describe coffee from the Indonesian island of the same name. Specialty buyers and producers use it to describe a specific Arabica varietal, Javanica, with a distinct plant structure, bean morphology, and cup profile that has nothing to do with where a coffee was grown. Before you can evaluate a Java lot, you need to know which Java you are talking about.</p>

<p class="body">This guide covers Java the varietal, not Java the island. Specifically, it covers what the Javanica cultivar produces in the cup, why it thrives at high altitude in Matagalpa Nicaragua, and how the washed and anaerobic versions from <a href="https://elquetzal.coffee/products/eq-washed-java-green-coffee" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" style="color: var(--gold); text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(201,168,76,0.35);">Finca El Quetzal</a> compare to each other and to the other specialty varieties grown on the same farm.</p>

